1
00:00:01,220 --> 00:00:05,160
In this video, we'll start
to develop a second type of

2
00:00:05,160 --> 00:00:06,810
recommender system called

3
00:00:06,810 --> 00:00:09,345
a content-based
filtering algorithm.

4
00:00:09,345 --> 00:00:11,790
To get started, let's
compare and contrast

5
00:00:11,790 --> 00:00:13,950
the collaborative filtering
approach that we'll be

6
00:00:13,950 --> 00:00:15,240
looking at so far with

7
00:00:15,240 --> 00:00:17,505
this new content-based
filtering approach.

8
00:00:17,505 --> 00:00:18,660
Let's take a look.

9
00:00:18,660 --> 00:00:21,045
With collaborative filtering,

10
00:00:21,045 --> 00:00:25,260
the general approach is that
we would recommend items to

11
00:00:25,260 --> 00:00:27,270
you based on ratings of

12
00:00:27,270 --> 00:00:30,735
users who gave similar
ratings as you.

13
00:00:30,735 --> 00:00:32,880
We have some number of users

14
00:00:32,880 --> 00:00:35,505
give some ratings
for some items,

15
00:00:35,505 --> 00:00:37,440
and the algorithm
figures out how to use

16
00:00:37,440 --> 00:00:40,500
that to recommend
new items to you.

17
00:00:40,500 --> 00:00:44,225
In contrast, content-based
filtering takes

18
00:00:44,225 --> 00:00:46,310
a different approach to

19
00:00:46,310 --> 00:00:48,805
deciding what to
recommend to you.

20
00:00:48,805 --> 00:00:51,065
A content-based
filtering algorithm

21
00:00:51,065 --> 00:00:53,330
will recommend items
to you based on

22
00:00:53,330 --> 00:00:55,220
the features of users and

23
00:00:55,220 --> 00:00:58,235
features of the items
to find a good match.

24
00:00:58,235 --> 00:00:59,600
In other words, it

25
00:00:59,600 --> 00:01:03,665
requires having some
features of each user,

26
00:01:03,665 --> 00:01:05,300
as well as some features of

27
00:01:05,300 --> 00:01:08,570
each item and it uses
those features to try to

28
00:01:08,570 --> 00:01:10,370
decide which items and

29
00:01:10,370 --> 00:01:13,620
users might be a good
match for each other.

30
00:01:13,620 --> 00:01:15,980
With a content-based
filtering algorithm,

31
00:01:15,980 --> 00:01:20,260
you still have data where
users have rated some items.

32
00:01:20,260 --> 00:01:22,490
Well, content-based filtering

33
00:01:22,490 --> 00:01:24,405
will continue to use r, i,

34
00:01:24,405 --> 00:01:28,850
j to denote whether
or not user j has

35
00:01:28,850 --> 00:01:33,650
rated item i and will
continue to use y i,

36
00:01:33,650 --> 00:01:35,780
j to denote the rating

37
00:01:35,780 --> 00:01:39,140
that user j is given
item i if it's defined.

38
00:01:39,140 --> 00:01:41,315
But the key to

39
00:01:41,315 --> 00:01:43,475
content-based filtering is that

40
00:01:43,475 --> 00:01:45,695
we will be able to
make good use of

41
00:01:45,695 --> 00:01:50,030
features of the user
and of the items to

42
00:01:50,030 --> 00:01:52,160
find better matches than

43
00:01:52,160 --> 00:01:53,690
potentially a pure collaborative

44
00:01:53,690 --> 00:01:55,640
filtering approach
might be able to.

45
00:01:55,640 --> 00:01:57,575
Let's take a look
at how this works.

46
00:01:57,575 --> 00:01:59,780
In the case of movie
recommendations,

47
00:01:59,780 --> 00:02:01,730
here are some
examples of features.

48
00:02:01,730 --> 00:02:04,250
You may know the
age of the user,

49
00:02:04,250 --> 00:02:08,360
or you may have the
gender of the user.

50
00:02:08,360 --> 00:02:11,765
This could be a one-hot feature

51
00:02:11,765 --> 00:02:14,240
similar to what you saw
when we were talking

52
00:02:14,240 --> 00:02:16,280
about decision trees where you

53
00:02:16,280 --> 00:02:18,395
could have a one-hot
feature with

54
00:02:18,395 --> 00:02:20,270
the values based on whether

55
00:02:20,270 --> 00:02:22,670
the user's
self-identified gender

56
00:02:22,670 --> 00:02:25,330
is male or female or unknown,

57
00:02:25,330 --> 00:02:29,565
and you may know the
country of the user.

58
00:02:29,565 --> 00:02:31,865
If there are about 200 countries

59
00:02:31,865 --> 00:02:33,230
in the world then also be

60
00:02:33,230 --> 00:02:37,850
a one-hot feature with
about 200 possible values.

61
00:02:37,850 --> 00:02:39,860
You can also look at
past behaviors of

62
00:02:39,860 --> 00:02:43,085
the user to construct
this feature vector.

63
00:02:43,085 --> 00:02:45,035
For example, if you look at

64
00:02:45,035 --> 00:02:47,675
the top thousand movies
in your catalog,

65
00:02:47,675 --> 00:02:51,500
you might construct a thousand
features that tells you of

66
00:02:51,500 --> 00:02:53,570
the thousand most
popular movies in

67
00:02:53,570 --> 00:02:56,815
the world which of these
has the user watch.

68
00:02:56,815 --> 00:03:00,530
In fact, you can also take
ratings the user might

69
00:03:00,530 --> 00:03:04,600
have already given in order
to construct new features.

70
00:03:04,600 --> 00:03:07,895
It turns out that if you
have a set of movies

71
00:03:07,895 --> 00:03:11,465
and if you know what
genre each movie is in,

72
00:03:11,465 --> 00:03:13,625
then the average rating

73
00:03:13,625 --> 00:03:16,295
per genre that the
user has given.

74
00:03:16,295 --> 00:03:21,065
Of all the romance movies
that the user has rated,

75
00:03:21,065 --> 00:03:22,530
what was the average rating?

76
00:03:22,530 --> 00:03:25,595
Of all the action movies
that the user has rated,

77
00:03:25,595 --> 00:03:27,245
what was the average rating?

78
00:03:27,245 --> 00:03:29,755
And so on for all
the other genres.

79
00:03:29,755 --> 00:03:34,985
This too can be a powerful
feature to describe the user.

80
00:03:34,985 --> 00:03:38,600
One interesting thing about
this feature is that it

81
00:03:38,600 --> 00:03:42,850
actually depends on the ratings
that the user had given.

82
00:03:42,850 --> 00:03:44,225
But there's nothing
wrong with that.

83
00:03:44,225 --> 00:03:46,280
Constructing a
feature vector that

84
00:03:46,280 --> 00:03:48,740
depends on the user's ratings is

85
00:03:48,740 --> 00:03:50,720
a completely fine way to

86
00:03:50,720 --> 00:03:53,600
